{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S6 â€” Lock the GitHub repo to a read-only mirror (repo-level ruleset)\n\n## Why\nEnforce that GitHub `main` can ONLY be advanced by the Gerrit replication identity. The\norg is on a free plan, so the lock is a REPO-LEVEL ruleset (admin-proof ORG-level rulesets\nrequire a paid plan). Accepted risk: trusted repo admins can edit/disable a repo-level\nruleset â€” explicitly accepted for this PoC. This is a one-way-door change (it replaces a\nhuman-PR protection model with a deploy-key-only push model and disables PRs/Issues/Actions),\nso the rationale, the ordering that avoids self-lockout, and a fast rollback are recorded\nbelow and in an ADR.\n\n## What\n- REPLACE the existing `main-protection` ruleset (DERISK E5: id 18048287, currently\n  `pull_request` + `required_status_checks` + `deletion` + `non_fast_forward`, admins\n  bypass-via-PR). That ruleset assumes a human PR workflow and is INCOMPATIBLE with the\n  mirror lock â€” the repo cannot both \"require human PRs\" and \"allow only the deploy key to\n  push\". The mirror lock disables/replaces it. **Before deleting it, snapshot its full\n  definition** (`gh api /repos/navapbc/rebar/rulesets/18048287 > infra/github/main-protection.snapshot.json`,\n  committed) so the prior protection model can be restored on rollback.\n- A repo-level ruleset (enforcement `active`) on `main` (+ the branch set the bot pushes):\n  rules `update` + `creation` + `deletion` + `non_fast_forward` (Restrict updates +\n  Restrict creations + Restrict deletions + Block force-pushes); bypass list = EXACTLY the\n  replication deploy key in \"Always allow\" mode.\n- A SEPARATE tag ruleset (`refs/tags/**`) with the SAME rules + the SAME bot bypass (else\n  tag pushes get rejected).\n- **Deploy-key bypass actor â€” DECIDED approach (not a spike).** The GitHub UI omits\n  DeployKey as a selectable bypass actor and terraform-provider-github has historically\n  rejected `actor_type = \"DeployKey\"`, so the bypass actor is set via a **committed,\n  idempotent `gh api` step**, NOT via the provider's `bypass_actors` block. The validated\n  REST payload (confirmed against this repo as admin) is:\n  - endpoint: `PUT /repos/navapbc/rebar/rulesets/{ruleset_id}` (full-object replacement, so\n    re-runs are idempotent â€” it replaces the whole `bypass_actors` array rather than\n    appending);\n  - bypass actor entry: `{ \"actor_type\": \"DeployKey\", \"actor_id\": null, \"bypass_mode\": \"always\" }`.\n  Terraform owns everything EXCEPT this one actor entry; the `gh api` step is wrapped in a\n  Terraform `null_resource` with `local-exec` + `depends_on` the ruleset so it is tracked in\n  state and re-applied on every run (no manual-step drift, no two-tool divergence). If a\n  future provider version gains DeployKey bypass support, the `null_resource` can be replaced\n  by a native `bypass_actors` block â€” this is recorded in the ADR.\n- **Self-lockout-safe ordering (verifiable).** The bypass actor MUST be present before the\n  branch/tag rulesets enforce, so apply in this fixed order in ONE `terraform apply` (no\n  manual gap): (1) create both rulesets with `enforcement = disabled`; (2) `null_resource`\n  registers the DeployKey bypass actor via the `gh api` PUT (`depends_on` the rulesets);\n  (3) a second `null_resource` (`depends_on` step 2) flips both rulesets to\n  `enforcement = active` via `gh api` PATCH. There is never a window where enforcement is\n  `active` with an empty bypass list.\n- **S5 prerequisite + cross-step data flow.** This story consumes the replication deploy key\n  created in S5. S6 reads the key via a `data \"github_repository_deploy_key\"` data source (or\n  a remote-state reference to S5's `deploy_key_id` output) â€” NOT a hand-copied numeric ID â€”\n  so the dependency is explicit, survives key rotation, and S6 cannot be applied/verified\n  until S5's key exists. (The REST bypass entry itself uses `actor_id: null` for DeployKey;\n  the data-source lookup confirms the key exists and that the bot identity matches before the\n  ruleset goes `active`.)\n- **Token scope (precondition).** The Terraform/`gh api` identity needs **Administration:\n  write** on `navapbc/rebar` (fine-grained PAT scoped to this single repo; or classic\n  `repo`) â€” ruleset management and repo-feature toggles require it, and it is a different,\n  broader scope than S5's deploy-key scope. The token is injected at apply time from a CI\n  secret (`TF_VAR_github_token`, declared `sensitive = true`, no default) and is NEVER\n  committed to a `.tfvars` file.\n- **Remote state.** `infra/terraform/github.tf` uses the shared remote backend with state\n  locking (the same backend the rest of `infra/terraform` uses) so concurrent applies can't\n  corrupt state or duplicate rulesets, and the GitHub token isn't cached in a local state\n  file. `terraform plan` is reviewed before every `apply`.\n- Mirror hygiene: turn OFF Pull Requests (the Feb-2026 repo setting â€” confirm the exact REST\n  field / `github_repository` attribute at implementation; PR-disable is distinct from\n  disabling merge methods), disable Issues + Actions; add a \"mirror â€” contribute via Gerrit\n  at rebar.solutions.navateam.com\" banner to the About + README; do NOT archive (archiving\n  freezes the replication bot too).\n\n## Scope\nIn: the GitHub-side lockdown + mirror hygiene + the S6â†’S5 wiring (data source / ordering /\nrollback). Out: the Gerrit-side replication itself (S5).\n\n**Dependency:** S6 must be applied AFTER S5 has created the replication deploy key (its\nexistence is a hard input to S6's bypass actor and ordering). Enforce this in IaC via the\n`data.github_repository_deploy_key` lookup (apply fails loudly if the key is absent) and via\n`depends_on`, so S6 can never go `active` with an empty bypass list.\n\n## Files\n- `infra/terraform/github.tf` â€” provider pin + `required_providers`, remote backend block,\n  sensitive `github_token` var, the two `github_repository_ruleset` resources (created\n  `disabled`), the `data.github_repository_deploy_key` lookup, the repo-feature toggles\n  (PRs/Issues/Actions off, banner), and the two `null_resource`s (bypass-actor PUT, then\n  enforcement flip to `active`).\n- `infra/github/set-bypass-actor.sh` â€” the idempotent `gh api PUT` script invoked by the\n  `null_resource` (full-object bypass_actors replacement; the validated DeployKey payload).\n- `infra/github/main-protection.snapshot.json` â€” committed snapshot of the old\n  `main-protection` ruleset (id 18048287), captured before deletion, for rollback.\n- `docs/adr/0006-github-mirror-lock.md` â€” ADR: repo-level-vs-org-level trade-off + accepted\n  admin-editability risk + why DeployKey bypass needs the `gh api` workaround (and the path\n  to retire it).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A direct `git push` to `main` by a non-bypass identity is REJECTED.\n- [ ] A PR-merge to `main` by a non-bypass identity is REJECTED (PRs are also disabled per\n      mirror hygiene).\n- [ ] A force-push to `main` is REJECTED.\n- [ ] A deletion of `main` (and of any bot-pushed branch in the ruleset's ref set) is REJECTED.\n- [ ] A tag push by a non-bypass identity is REJECTED by the separate `refs/tags/**` ruleset.\n- [ ] The replication deploy key CAN push `main` (it is the SOLE bypass actor, \"Always allow\",\n      on the branch ruleset).\n- [ ] The replication deploy key CAN push tags (it is the SOLE bypass actor, \"Always allow\",\n      on the `refs/tags/**` ruleset).\n- [ ] The DeployKey bypass actor is set via the committed `gh api` PUT step (validated payload\n      `{actor_type:\"DeployKey\", actor_id:null, bypass_mode:\"always\"}`), is the ONLY entry in\n      each ruleset's `bypass_actors`, and re-running the apply is idempotent (no duplicate /\n      no removal of the actor).\n- [ ] Ordering is enforced: rulesets are created `disabled`, the bypass actor is registered,\n      THEN enforcement flips to `active` â€” verified by `gh api` showing each ruleset\n      `enforcement: active` WITH the DeployKey bypass present (never `active` + empty bypass).\n- [ ] The S6 ruleset obtains the deploy key via a Terraform data source / remote-state\n      reference (not a hand-copied ID); applying S6 before S5's key exists fails loudly.\n- [ ] Pull Requests are disabled (Feb-2026 setting).\n- [ ] Issues are disabled.\n- [ ] Actions are disabled.\n- [ ] The README and the About carry the \"mirror â€” contribute via Gerrit\" banner.\n- [ ] The repo is NOT archived.\n- [ ] The pre-existing `main-protection` ruleset (id 18048287, PR + required-status-checks\n      model) is replaced/disabled, and its definition is snapshotted to\n      `infra/github/main-protection.snapshot.json` before deletion.\n- [ ] A rollback path is documented and runnable in under ~15 min: `gh api PATCH\n      /repos/navapbc/rebar/rulesets/{id} -f enforcement=disabled` to instantly suspend the\n      mirror lock if the bot is locked out, plus restore of `main-protection` from the\n      snapshot and re-enable of PRs/Issues/Actions.\n- [ ] The Terraform/`gh api` identity's required scope is documented (Administration: write,\n      fine-grained PAT scoped to this repo) and the token is injected from a CI secret as a\n      `sensitive` var, never committed to `.tfvars`.\n- [ ] `infra/terraform/github.tf` uses the shared remote backend with state locking.\n- [ ] `docs/adr/0006-github-mirror-lock.md` records: repo-level vs org-level trade-off, the\n      accepted admin-editability risk, and the DeployKey `gh api` workaround (+ retirement path).\n- [ ] The accepted risk is recorded: the repo-level ruleset is editable by trusted repo admins\n      (free org -> no admin-proof org-level rule). Confirmed: navapbc is a `free` org; Issues\n      are already disabled; 0 deploy keys exist today (S5 adds the replication key)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782689174491022001,"uuid":"e789806b-a4a6-41fd-a5ba-52f63e6178c8"}